code:
// PERFORMANCE PROBLEM — slow for ONE user
// Query without index on a 10M row table
// SELECT * FROM orders WHERE customer_id = 123;
// → Full table scan: O(n) — 10M rows checked for every query
// Fix: CREATE INDEX idx_customer ON orders(customer_id);
// → Index lookup: O(log n) — fast regardless of load

// SCALABILITY PROBLEM — fast for one user, slow under load
// Single server setup:
//   1 user  → 10ms response ✓
//   1000 users simultaneously → 10000ms response ✗ (server overwhelmed)
//
// Adding more servers (horizontal scaling) solves this:
// Load Balancer → [Server 1, Server 2, Server 3]
//   1000 users → distributed across 3 servers → ~333 users each → 10ms ✓

// Latency vs Throughput (related concept):
// Latency:    time for ONE operation (e.g., 10ms per request)
// Throughput: operations per unit time (e.g., 1000 requests/second)
// Goal: maximize throughput with acceptable latency
// These often conflict: optimizing for throughput (batch processing)
// can increase individual request latency

// VERTICAL SCALING (Scale Up)
// Before: 1 server with 4 CPU, 16GB RAM → handles 1000 req/sec
// After:  1 server with 32 CPU, 128GB RAM → handles 8000 req/sec
// Pros: Simple, no app changes needed
// Cons: Expensive, has upper limit, single point of failure
//       AWS largest instance: ~448 vCPU, 24TB RAM (then you're stuck)

// HORIZONTAL SCALING (Scale Out)
// Before: 1 server → handles 1000 req/sec
// After:  10 servers + Load Balancer → handles 10000 req/sec
//
// Architecture:
// Client → DNS → Load Balancer → [App Server 1]
//                              → [App Server 2]
//                              → [App Server 3]
//                                    ↓
//                              Shared Database
//                              Shared Cache (Redis)
//
// KEY REQUIREMENT for horizontal scaling:
// Application must be STATELESS
// ✗ WRONG: User session stored in App Server 1's memory
//   → User's next request goes to App Server 2 → session not found!
// ✓ RIGHT: Session stored in shared Redis/Database
//   → Any server can handle any user's request

// When to use which:
// < 1000 req/sec, early stage → Vertical (simple)
// > 1000 req/sec, HA required → Horizontal (scalable)

// Load Balancer placement:
// Client → [Load Balancer] → Server 1
//                         → Server 2
//                         → Server 3

// ALGORITHMS:

// 1. Round Robin — sequential distribution
// Request 1 → Server 1
// Request 2 → Server 2
// Request 3 → Server 3
// Request 4 → Server 1 (back to start)

// 2. Weighted Round Robin — proportional to capacity
// Server 1 (powerful): weight 3 → gets 3 out of 5 requests
// Server 2 (normal):   weight 2 → gets 2 out of 5 requests

// 3. Least Connections
// Server 1: 100 active connections
// Server 2: 50 active connections  ← new request goes here
// Server 3: 75 active connections

// 4. IP Hash (sticky sessions)
// hash(client_ip) % num_servers = target server
// Same client always hits same server — session consistency

// LAYER 4 vs LAYER 7:

// L4 — sees only IP + port, fast, no content inspection
// Client:80 → LB → Server:8080
// No idea what HTTP method, URL, or headers contain

// L7 — sees full HTTP, flexible routing
// GET /api/users → Route to API servers
// GET /images/   → Route to CDN/Image servers
// POST /upload/  → Route to Upload servers
// Cookie: session=admin → Route to Admin servers

// Health checks:
// Load balancer pings: GET /health → expects 200 OK
// If server returns 5xx or times out → removed from pool
// When healthy again → added back to pool

// DNS RESOLUTION FLOW:
// Browser types: www.github.com
//
// Step 1: Check browser DNS cache → miss
// Step 2: Check OS DNS cache → miss
// Step 3: Query ISP Recursive Resolver
//   Step 3a: Resolver queries Root Nameserver → returns .com TLD server
//   Step 3b: Resolver queries .com TLD → returns github.com nameserver
//   Step 3c: Resolver queries github.com nameserver → returns IP: 140.82.121.4
// Step 4: Browser caches IP (for TTL duration), connects to 140.82.121.4

// DNS Record types:
// A record:     domain → IPv4 address    (github.com → 140.82.121.4)
// AAAA record:  domain → IPv6 address
// CNAME:        alias → canonical name   (www.github.com → github.com)
// MX record:    mail server for domain

// CDN FLOW:
// WITHOUT CDN:
// User (India) → Origin Server (Virginia) → 300ms latency

// WITH CDN:
// User (India) → CDN Edge (Mumbai)
//   Cache HIT: CDN serves from cache → 10ms latency
//   Cache MISS: CDN fetches from origin (Virginia), caches it
//               → 300ms first time, but cached for subsequent users

// What CDN caches:
// ✓ Static: images, CSS, JS, HTML, videos
// ✗ Dynamic: user-specific data, API responses with personal info

// CDN providers: CloudFront (AWS), Cloudflare, Akamai, Fastly

// CDN Push vs Pull:
// Push: You upload content to CDN (good for known static assets)
// Pull: CDN fetches from origin on first miss (good for dynamic sites)

// CAP Theorem visualization:
//
//          Consistency
//          /         \
//    CP systems    CA systems
//   (impossible in    (only for
//    distributed)   single node)
//         \         /
//    AP systems
//
// Since partitions always happen in distributed systems:
// Real choice = CP vs AP

// CP — Consistency + Partition Tolerance (sacrifice Availability)
// Example: Bank transfers, inventory systems
//
// Scenario: Network partition between Node A and Node B
// User writes balance = $1000 to Node A
// Node A cannot sync to Node B (partition!)
// User reads from Node B:
//   CP system: returns ERROR or blocks until partition heals
//   → Correct but unavailable during partition

// AP — Availability + Partition Tolerance (sacrifice Consistency)
// Example: Social media timeline, DNS, shopping cart
//
// Same partition scenario:
// User reads from Node B:
//   AP system: returns stale data (old balance, old post count)
//   → Available but possibly inconsistent
//   Eventually when partition heals, nodes sync → eventual consistency

// Real-world examples:
// CP: HBase, Zookeeper, etcd, MongoDB (with strong consistency)
// AP: DynamoDB, Cassandra, CouchDB, DNS

// Interview answer template:
// "For [banking/payments/inventory], I'd choose CP because showing
//  wrong data would cause financial loss or overselling.
//  For [social feed/shopping cart/DNS], I'd choose AP because
//  serving slightly stale data is acceptable and availability matters more."

// STRONG CONSISTENCY — all reads see latest write immediately
// Banking example:
// Account balance: $1000
// T1: Withdraw $200 (write $800 to all replicas synchronously)
// T2: Check balance from any replica → always sees $800 ✓
// Cost: Write latency higher (must wait for all replicas to confirm)
//
// Implementation: Two-phase commit, Paxos, Raft consensus

// EVENTUAL CONSISTENCY — reads may be stale, eventually converge
// DNS example:
// Admin updates DNS: example.com → new IP 1.2.3.4
// 0 minutes: Some resolvers still return old IP 1.2.3.3
// 30 minutes: More resolvers return new IP
// 24 hours: All DNS resolvers worldwide return 1.2.3.4
// → "Eventually" all agree, but not immediately
//
// DynamoDB/Cassandra: eventual consistency by default
// Read-your-own-writes consistency: you always see your own writes,
//   but may not see others' recent writes

// WEAK CONSISTENCY — no guarantees, get what's available
// VoIP call example:
// Network drops 3 seconds of audio
// Caller can't hear those 3 seconds — GONE
// System does NOT buffer and replay them (that would be weird)
// Just continue with current audio stream
// Live video streaming: similar — skip lost frames, show current frame
//
// Memcached: weak consistency — data may not be there at all (eviction)

// Tradeoff summary:
// Strong:    Correct always. Highest latency. Use for money/inventory.
// Eventual:  Fast writes. Brief staleness OK. Use for social/DNS/carts.
// Weak:      Fastest. No guarantees. Use for real-time streams.

// AVAILABILITY NINES — what they mean in real downtime:
// 99%     = 87.6 hours/year  = 7.3 hours/month  (unacceptable for prod)
// 99.9%   = 8.76 hours/year  = 43.8 min/month   (acceptable, some services)
// 99.99%  = 52.6 min/year    = 4.38 min/month   (good, most prod services)
// 99.999% = 5.26 min/year    = 26.3 sec/month   (excellent, critical infra)

// IMPROVING AVAILABILITY:

// 1. Eliminate Single Points of Failure (SPOF)
// SPOF: [Client] → [Single Server] → [Single DB]
//   Server down = 0% availability
// No SPOF: [Client] → [LB] → [Server 1, Server 2]
//                          → [DB Primary + Replica]

// 2. Active-Passive Failover
// Primary handles all traffic
// Passive is standby, replicating from primary
// Health check detects primary failure
// Passive promoted to primary in seconds
// Downtime = failover time (~30 seconds typical)

// 3. Active-Active (no failover needed)
// Both servers handle traffic simultaneously
// If one fails, other handles all traffic
// No failover delay — immediate recovery
// More complex: both must stay in sync

// 4. Circuit Breaker Pattern
// Without circuit breaker:
// ServiceA → calls ServiceB (ServiceB is slow/down)
// ServiceA threads pile up waiting → ServiceA crashes too
//
// With circuit breaker:
// ServiceA → CircuitBreaker monitors ServiceB call success rate
// If failure rate > threshold → circuit OPENS
// All ServiceB calls fail fast (no waiting) → return fallback
// After timeout → circuit HALF-OPEN → try one request
// If succeeds → circuit CLOSES → normal operation resumes

// SQL — structured, ACID, joins, complex queries
// Schema defined upfront:
CREATE TABLE orders (
    order_id    BIGINT PRIMARY KEY,
    customer_id BIGINT REFERENCES customers(id),  -- foreign key
    total       DECIMAL(10,2) NOT NULL,
    created_at  TIMESTAMP DEFAULT NOW()
);

-- Complex query with JOIN:
SELECT c.name, SUM(o.total) as total_spend
FROM customers c
JOIN orders o ON c.id = o.customer_id
WHERE o.created_at > '2024-01-01'
GROUP BY c.name
HAVING SUM(o.total) > 1000;

// ACID transaction:
BEGIN;
  UPDATE accounts SET balance = balance - 100 WHERE id = 1;
  UPDATE accounts SET balance = balance + 100 WHERE id = 2;
COMMIT;  -- both succeed or both fail — no partial state

// NoSQL — flexible, scalable, specific patterns
// Key-Value (Redis): O(1) lookup, no queries
// GET user:1234:session → {"userId":1234, "token":"abc..."}

// Document (MongoDB): flexible schema
// db.users.insertOne({
//   name: "Harsh",
//   skills: ["Java", "Python"],  // arrays — hard in SQL
//   address: { city: "San Jose", zip: "95110" }  // nested — no joins needed
// });

// Wide Column (Cassandra): designed for massive writes
// Partition key = userId → all writes for user go to same node
// Excellent for: time-series, activity feeds, IoT

// Decision guide:
// Need ACID transactions, complex joins → SQL
// Need flexible schema, massive scale → NoSQL
// Need session/cache data → Redis (Key-Value)
// Need social graph → Neo4j (Graph)
// Need 99.99% write availability → Cassandra (Wide-column)

// LEADER-FOLLOWER REPLICATION
//
// Architecture:
// [Leader DB] ←── Writes only
//      │
//      ├──async replication──→ [Follower 1]
//      ├──async replication──→ [Follower 2]
//      └──async replication──→ [Follower 3]
//                                    ↑
//                               Reads distributed here
//
// Write path: App → Leader → async→ Followers
// Read path:  App → Any Follower (or Leader)

// SYNCHRONOUS vs ASYNCHRONOUS replication:
// Synchronous:
//   App writes → Leader persists → waits for Follower ACK → returns success
//   ✓ No data loss on leader failure
//   ✗ Write latency = Leader time + network + Follower time
//
// Asynchronous:
//   App writes → Leader persists → immediately returns success → replicates later
//   ✓ Low write latency
//   ✗ If leader crashes before replication: data loss!
//   ✗ Followers may serve stale reads

// FAILOVER when leader fails:
// Step 1: Detect leader failure (health check timeout)
// Step 2: Elect new leader (follower with most recent data)
// Step 3: Update clients/load balancer to point to new leader
// Step 4: Old leader (if it recovers) becomes follower
// Downtime during failover: typically 30-60 seconds

// READ SCALING example:
// Without replication: 1 DB → 1000 reads/sec max
// With 4 replicas:     5 DB servers → 5000 reads/sec (reads distributed)
// Write capacity unchanged: still 1 leader

// Replication lag:
// Leader processes write at T=0
// Follower applies write at T=50ms (replication lag)
// Read to follower at T=10ms → returns OLD data
// Read to follower at T=100ms → returns NEW data
// This is eventual consistency

// SHARDING — splitting data across multiple DB instances
//
// Without sharding: 1 DB, 1B users → 1 TB of data, too slow
// With sharding: 4 shards, 250M users each → manageable

// STRATEGY 1: Range-based sharding
// Shard 1: user_id 0       - 250,000,000
// Shard 2: user_id 250M    - 500,000,000
// Shard 3: user_id 500M    - 750,000,000
// Shard 4: user_id 750M    - 1,000,000,000
// ✓ Range queries easy (get users 100-200 → only Shard 1)
// ✗ Hotspot risk if early users are most active

// STRATEGY 2: Hash-based sharding
// shard = hash(user_id) % 4
// user_id=1000 → hash=2847 → 2847%4=3 → Shard 3
// user_id=1001 → hash=9123 → 9123%4=1 → Shard 1
// ✓ Even distribution — no hotspots
// ✗ Range queries require querying ALL shards
// ✗ Adding shard changes modulo → massive data movement!

// SOLUTION: Consistent Hashing
// Virtual ring with positions 0 to 2^32
// Servers placed at positions on ring
// Key maps to clockwise nearest server
// Adding server: only keys between new server and
//   its predecessor need to move — minimal disruption

// STRATEGY 3: Directory-based
// Lookup table:
// user 1000 → Shard A
// user 1001 → Shard B
// ✓ Maximum flexibility — any key to any shard
// ✗ Lookup table = SPOF and bottleneck

// CROSS-SHARD QUERY PROBLEM:
// SELECT * FROM users JOIN orders ON users.id = orders.user_id
// If users on Shard 1-4 and orders on Shard 1-4:
// Must query ALL shards and merge → slow, complex
// Solution: co-locate user and their orders on same shard
// (shard both users and orders by user_id)

// WITHOUT INDEX — full table scan O(n)
-- 10 million users, find Harsh:
SELECT * FROM users WHERE email = 'harsh@example.com';
-- Database checks every row: 10M comparisons → SLOW

// WITH INDEX — B-Tree lookup O(log n)
CREATE INDEX idx_email ON users(email);
-- Database traverses B-Tree: ~23 comparisons (log2 10M) → FAST

// B-TREE STRUCTURE (simplified):
//
//              [M]
//            /      \
//         [G]       [R]
//        /   \     /   \
//      [D]  [J]  [N]  [T]
//
// Find 'harsh@...' → traverse: M>h, G<h, J<h → narrow quickly

// CLUSTERED INDEX:
// Rows physically stored in primary key order
CREATE CLUSTERED INDEX idx_pk ON orders(order_id);
-- order_id 1,2,3...1000 stored sequentially on disk
-- Range query: SELECT * FROM orders WHERE order_id BETWEEN 100 AND 200
-- → Read contiguous disk blocks → very fast (one disk seek)

// NON-CLUSTERED INDEX:
// Separate structure with pointers to rows
CREATE INDEX idx_customer ON orders(customer_id);
-- Index: customer_id=5 → [pointers to rows with customer_id=5]
-- Rows for customer 5 may be scattered across disk → more disk seeks

// WHEN TO INDEX:
// ✓ Columns in WHERE, JOIN, ORDER BY frequently
// ✓ High cardinality columns (many distinct values: email, user_id)
// ✗ Low cardinality columns (gender, boolean — index rarely helps)
// ✗ Write-heavy tables (constant index maintenance overhead)
// ✗ Small tables (full scan might be faster than index overhead)

// COMPOSITE INDEX:
CREATE INDEX idx_user_date ON orders(user_id, created_at);
-- SELECT * FROM orders WHERE user_id=5 AND created_at > '2024-01-01'
-- Uses both columns — very efficient
-- Note: prefix matters! (user_id alone uses this index, created_at alone doesn't)

// CACHE-ASIDE (most common in practice)
class UserService {
    Cache cache;
    Database db;

    User getUser(int userId) {
        // Step 1: Check cache
        User cached = cache.get("user:" + userId);
        if (cached != null) return cached;  // CACHE HIT

        // Step 2: Cache miss → query DB
        User user = db.findById(userId);

        // Step 3: Store in cache for future requests
        cache.set("user:" + userId, user, TTL_1_HOUR);

        return user;  // CACHE MISS — slower this time
    }

    void updateUser(int userId, User updated) {
        db.save(updated);              // Write to DB
        cache.delete("user:" + userId); // Invalidate cache
        // Next read will repopulate cache from fresh DB data
    }
}

// READ-THROUGH — cache handles misses automatically
// Application only talks to cache:
// App → Cache [HIT] → return data
// App → Cache [MISS] → Cache fetches from DB → stores → returns
// App never directly talks to DB

// WRITE-THROUGH — write to both cache and DB synchronously
void writeThrough(String key, Object value) {
    db.save(key, value);    // persist to DB first
    cache.set(key, value);  // then update cache
    // Both succeed before returning — consistent but slow
}

// WRITE-BEHIND — write to cache, flush to DB asynchronously
void writeBehind(String key, Object value) {
    cache.set(key, value);           // fast — return immediately
    asyncQueue.enqueue(key, value);  // DB write happens later in background
    // RISK: if cache crashes before flush → data lost!
    // USE FOR: shopping cart, view counters, analytics
}

// Cache TTL (Time To Live):
// Short TTL: frequent DB reads but fresh data
// Long TTL:  fewer DB reads but stale data risk
// No TTL:    cache-aside with explicit invalidation on write

// LRU — Least Recently Used
// Cache: [A, B, C, D] (capacity 4, A=oldest access, D=newest)
// New request for E:
//   Evict A (least recently used)
//   Cache: [B, C, D, E]
// Access B:
//   Cache: [C, D, E, B] (B moved to most recent)

// LFU — Least Frequently Used
// Cache with access counts: {A:10, B:3, C:8, D:1}
// New item E needs space:
//   Evict D (frequency=1, lowest)
//   Cache: {A:10, C:8, B:3, E:1}

// Redis supports: LRU, LFU, Random, TTL-based eviction
// Configure in redis.conf:
// maxmemory-policy allkeys-lru    # evict any key LRU when full
// maxmemory-policy allkeys-lfu    # evict LFU when full
// maxmemory-policy volatile-lru   # only evict keys with TTL set

// CACHE STAMPEDE (Thundering Herd):
// Popular key "homepage" expires at T=0
// 1000 concurrent requests all miss cache at T=0
// All 1000 query the database simultaneously → DB overwhelmed

// Fix 1: Mutex/lock on cache population
void getWithMutex(String key) {
    Object value = cache.get(key);
    if (value != null) return value;

    if (mutex.tryLock(key)) {   // only ONE thread gets lock
        try {
            value = db.query(key);
            cache.set(key, value, TTL);
        } finally { mutex.unlock(key); }
    } else {
        Thread.sleep(50);         // other threads wait briefly
        return cache.get(key);    // then read from cache (now populated)
    }
}

// Fix 2: Probabilistic early refresh
// Refresh cache BEFORE expiry based on remaining TTL probability
// Prevents the exact TTL moment from being hit by many requests

// CACHE AVALANCHE:
// Bad: all keys expire at exactly the same time (same TTL)
// cache.set("key1", v1, 3600);  // all expire at hour mark
// cache.set("key2", v2, 3600);
// cache.set("key3", v3, 3600);

// Fix: Add random jitter to TTL
int jitter = random.nextInt(600);  // 0-10 minutes random
cache.set("key1", v1, 3600 + jitter);  // expire at different times

// REDIS DATA STRUCTURES AND USE CASES

// 1. STRING — simple values, counters
redis.set("user:1:name", "Harsh");
redis.incr("page:home:views");      // atomic counter increment
redis.setex("session:abc123", 3600, userId);  // with TTL

// 2. HASH — object fields (avoid serialization overhead)
redis.hset("user:1", "name", "Harsh", "email", "h@e.com", "age", "25");
redis.hget("user:1", "email");      // get one field — no deserialize
redis.hgetall("user:1");            // get all fields

// 3. LIST — queues, activity feeds
redis.lpush("jobQueue", "job1", "job2");  // add to left
redis.rpop("jobQueue");                    // pop from right (FIFO)
redis.lrange("feed:user1", 0, 9);         // get first 10 items

// 4. SET — unique values, tags
redis.sadd("post:100:tags", "java", "programming");
redis.smembers("post:100:tags");           // get all tags
redis.sismember("online:users", "userId"); // O(1) membership check

// 5. SORTED SET — leaderboards, rate limiting
redis.zadd("leaderboard", 9500, "Harsh");  // add with score
redis.zadd("leaderboard", 8200, "Alex");
redis.zrevrange("leaderboard", 0, 9, WITHSCORES);  // top 10
redis.zrank("leaderboard", "Harsh");       // rank of player

// RATE LIMITING with Sorted Set:
void rateLimit(String userId) {
    String key = "rate:" + userId;
    long now = System.currentTimeMillis();
    long windowStart = now - 60000;  // 1 minute window

    redis.zremrangebyscore(key, 0, windowStart);  // remove old requests
    long count = redis.zcard(key);                 // count in window
    if (count >= 100) throw new RateLimitException("Too many requests");
    redis.zadd(key, now, now + "");  // add current request
    redis.expire(key, 60);           // cleanup after 1 min
}

// DISTRIBUTED LOCK:
boolean acquired = redis.set(
    "lock:resource",
    "unique-id",
    "NX",     // Only set if not exists
    "EX",     // Set expiry
    30        // 30 seconds — auto-release if process crashes
);
if (acquired) {
    try { doWork(); }
    finally { redis.del("lock:resource"); }  // release
}

// MESSAGE QUEUE — core problem illustration

// WITHOUT message queue — tight coupling, no load leveling
class OrderService {
    void placeOrder(Order order) {
        paymentService.charge(order);       // direct call — payment must be up
        inventoryService.reserve(order);    // direct call — inventory must be up
        notificationService.notify(order);  // direct call — notification must be up
        // If ANY service is down → order fails!
        // If 10000 orders/sec spike → all services overwhelmed!
    }
}

// WITH message queue — decoupled, load-leveled
class OrderService {
    void placeOrder(Order order) {
        db.save(order);                    // save order
        messageQueue.publish("order.created", order);  // fire and forget
        // OrderService doesn't care who processes or when
        // Returns success immediately
    }
}

// Consumers process at their own pace:
class PaymentConsumer    { void consume(Order o) { /* process payment */ } }
class InventoryConsumer  { void consume(Order o) { /* reserve stock */ } }
class NotificationConsumer { void consume(Order o) { /* send email */ } }

// KAFKA vs RABBITMQ:

// KAFKA — event stream, persistent, replayable
// Topic: "user-activity" retains all events for 7 days
// Consumer Group A (Analytics): reads from beginning, builds dashboards
// Consumer Group B (ML):        reads from beginning, trains models
// Consumer Group C (Realtime):  reads latest events only
// All three groups independently consume same stream
// Message persists after consumption — can replay!
// Throughput: millions of messages/second

// RABBITMQ — task queue, consumed and gone
// Queue: "email-jobs" — each job consumed by ONE worker
// 5 email workers compete to process jobs
// Once worker processes → message DELETED from queue
// Cannot replay — designed for task distribution not event log
// Better routing: Direct/Fanout/Topic/Headers exchanges

// MONOLITH — single deployable unit
// Single Spring Boot application:
// ├── UserModule
// ├── OrderModule
// ├── InventoryModule
// └── NotificationModule
//     All share same database, same JVM, same deployment
//
// Deploy: build ONE jar, deploy to ONE server
// Scale:  duplicate ENTIRE application
// Debug:  single log file, single call stack

// MICROSERVICES — separate services
// User Service     (Port 8081) → Users DB
// Order Service    (Port 8082) → Orders DB
// Inventory Service(Port 8083) → Inventory DB
// Notification Service (async) → No DB (stateless)
//
// Deploy: 4 separate deployments, independent
// Scale:  scale only Order Service if orders spike
// Debug:  distributed tracing (Jaeger/Zipkin) to follow request across services

// COMMUNICATION between microservices:
// Synchronous: REST calls, gRPC
//   OrderService → HTTP GET → UserService/users/123
//   Simple but creates coupling — if UserService is down, order fails

// Asynchronous: Message queues (preferred)
//   OrderService publishes → Kafka "order.created"
//   InventoryService consumes → reserve stock
//   NotificationService consumes → send email
//   Services are decoupled — UserService can be down, order still placed

// DATA CONSISTENCY across services:
// No shared database → no distributed transactions
// SAGA PATTERN: sequence of local transactions + compensating transactions
// Order placed:
//   Step 1: Order Service saves order (local transaction)
//   Step 2: Payment Service charges card
//   Step 3: Inventory Service reserves stock
// If Step 3 fails:
//   Compensation: Payment Service refunds card
//   Compensation: Order Service cancels order

// WHEN TO USE WHAT:
// Team < 10, early stage, unclear domain → Monolith
// Team > 20, clear domain boundaries, scale needed → Microservices
// Mixed: start monolith, extract services when needed

// SIMPLE MODULO HASHING — fails when servers change
// 3 servers: hash(key) % 3
// key="user1" → hash=1000 → 1000%3=1 → Server 1
// key="user2" → hash=2000 → 2000%3=2 → Server 2

// Add 4th server: hash(key) % 4
// key="user1" → hash=1000 → 1000%4=0 → Server 0 (WAS Server 1!)
// key="user2" → hash=2000 → 2000%4=0 → Server 0 (WAS Server 2!)
// Result: ~75% of keys remapped → massive cache miss storm!

// CONSISTENT HASHING — minimal disruption
// Virtual ring: 0 ────────────────────────→ 2^32 (wraps around)
//
//    0                           2^32
//    |    Server A               |
//    |       ↑                   |
//    |   hash(A)                 |
//    ├───────┤──────Server B─────┤
//    |       |      ↑            |
//    |  Keys here   hash(B)      |
//    |  go to A                  |
//
// Key assignment: go clockwise from key's position → first server you hit
// key→position 50 → clockwise → Server A at 100 → assigned to Server A
// key→position 150 → clockwise → Server B at 200 → assigned to Server B

// Add Server C at position 250:
//   Only keys between Server B (200) and Server C (250) move to Server C
//   All other keys unchanged — minimal disruption!

// VIRTUAL NODES — even distribution
// Without vnodes: Server A owns arc from 0-300, Server B owns 300-700
// Server A gets 37.5% of key space, Server B gets 50% — uneven!

// With vnodes (3 vnodes each):
// Server A: positions 100, 400, 700
// Server B: positions 200, 500, 800
// Now each arc between servers is ~100 units
// Server A and Server B each own ~50% of key space — balanced!

// Server C added with vnodes at 150, 450, 750:
// Each existing server loses roughly 1/3 of its load
// New load evenly taken from A AND B — not just one neighbor

// Used in: Amazon DynamoDB, Apache Cassandra, Memcached (ketama),
//          load balancers, distributed caches

