// SYSTEM DESIGN FRAMEWORK — applied to designing a URL shortener:

// STEP 1: REQUIREMENTS CLARIFICATION
// Functional:
//   - Shorten a long URL to a short code
//   - Redirect short URL to original
//   - Custom aliases (optional)
//   - Analytics: click count, geography
// Non-functional:
//   - 100M URLs created per day
//   - 10:1 read:write ratio → 1B redirects/day
//   - Redirect must be < 10ms latency (99th percentile)
//   - 99.99% availability
//   - URLs never deleted (or expire after 5 years)

// STEP 2: CAPACITY ESTIMATION
// Writes:  100M/day = 100M/86400 ≈ 1,157 writes/sec
// Reads:   1B/day ≈ 11,574 reads/sec
// Storage: 100M URLs/day × 500 bytes × 365 days × 5 years = 91 TB
// Cache:   Top 20% URLs get 80% traffic (Pareto)
//          Cache 20% of daily reads × 500B = 1B × 0.2 × 500B = 100 GB
//          (1 Redis cluster handles this)

// STEP 3: HIGH-LEVEL DESIGN
// [Client]
//    ↓ HTTPS
// [CDN / Load Balancer]
//    ↓
// [URL Service (stateless, horizontally scalable)]
//    ↓              ↓
// [Redis Cache]  [MySQL DB + Read Replicas]
// (short→long)   (persistent store)

// STEP 4: DEEP DIVE
// Short code generation: Auto-increment ID → Base62 encoding
// Sharding: by short_code hash (read scalability)
// Caching: cache-aside, TTL=7 days (URLs don't change)
// Redirect: HTTP 302 (track analytics)
// Analytics: async, publish to Kafka on each redirect
//            Kafka → Analytics Service → ClickHouse
// Failure handling: Redis miss → DB read → repopulate cache
//                   DB down → serve from cache (stale but better than error)

// TRADEOFFS TO MENTION:
// 301 vs 302: Performance vs analytics tracking
// SQL vs NoSQL: SQL for simplicity (data fits on one shard initially)
// Cache TTL: Long TTL = better performance, Short TTL = fresher data
// Short code length: 7 chars = 3.5T combos (enough for 100M/day × 96 years)

